 Industrial Accidents in Communist East Germany -- tLabor’s Risks: Work Accidents, the Industrial Wage Relation, and Social Insurance in Socialist Romania -- tNuclear Yutopia: The Outcome of the First Nuclear Accident in Yugoslavia, 1958 -- tPART IV: WORKERS, PROTEST, AND REFORM -- tStrikes in Czechoslovakia, 1945–1968: Systems Analysis and the Debate over the Causes of the Collapse of State Socialism -- t“It Shall Not Be a Written Gift, but a Lived Reality”: Equal Pay, Women’s Work, and the Politics of Labor in State-Socialist Hungary, Late 1960s to Late 1970s -- tLabor Protest in the Italian-Yugoslav Border Region During the Cold War: Action, Control, Legitimacy, Self- Management -- tWhen Workers’ Self-Management Met Neoliberalism: Positive Perceptions of Market Reforms among Blue-Collar Workers in Late Yugoslav Socialism -- tPART V: TOWARD AN INCLUSIVE HISTORY OF WORK -- tNot Just Socialist Miners, but Miners of the World: Internationalism, Global Trends, and Romanian Coal Workers -- tList of Contributors -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLabor regimes under communism in East-Central Europe were complex, shifting, and ambiguous. This collection of sixteen essays offers new conceptual and empirical ways to understand their history from the end of World War II to 1989, and to think about how their experiences relate to debates about labor history, both European and global. The authors reconsider the history of state socialism by re-examining the policies and problems of communist regimes and recovering the voices of the workers who built them. The contributors look at work and workers in Albania, Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, the German Democratic Republic, Hungary, Poland, Romania, and Yugoslavia. They explore the often contentious relationship between politics and labor policy, dealing with diverse topics including workers’ safety and risks; labor rights and protests; working women’s politics and professions; migrant workers and social welfare; attempts to control workers’ behavior and stem unemployment; and cases of incomplete, compromised, or even abandoned processes of proletarianization. Workers are presented as active agents in resisting and supporting changes in labor policies, in choosing allegiances, and in defining the very nature of work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aLaborzEurope, CentralxHistoryy20th century. 0aLaborzEurope, EasternxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocialismzEurope, CentralxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocialismzEurope, EasternxHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Communism, Post-Communism & Socialism.2bisacsh  aCommunism, Central and Eastern Europe, Labor history, Protests, Self-management, Women.1 aAlamgir, Alena K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArcher, Rory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartha, Eszter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonfiglioli, Chiara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrunnbauer, Ulf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCucu, Alina-Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlont, Anca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrama, Adrian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeumos, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJarska, Natalia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLindenberger, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMazurek, Małgorzata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r